irst national newspaper strike ballot in over a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://safc.blog/red-socks-pinstripes-fighting-the-bosses-who-is-the-charlie-methven-in-safc-takeover/|title=Red socks, pinstripes, fighting the bosses. Who is the Charlie Methven in SAFC takeover?}}</ref> The dispute was settled afterward, but Methven left The Telegraph to join the [[London Evening Standard]] in 2004, as a feature writer.\n\n===Publisher===\n\nIn 2005, in a consortium that included former ''Daily Telegraph'' Director Jeremy Deedes, Methven founded a daily horseracing and gambling newspaper titled ''The Sportsman''; it was the UK's first new nationally distributed newspaper since ''The Independent'' in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/4686285.stm|title=Is new gambling paper on to a winner?|date=15 July 2005|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> While the paper reached a circulation of over 20,000 copies a day, it ran out of funds in late 2006 and folded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/owners-put-their-cards-on-table-for-sportsman-launch/|title=Owners put their cards on table for Sportsman launch|first=Press Gazette|last=Twitter|date= 14 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Public relations===\n\nIn 2011, he co-founded a communications consultancy called Dragon Associates (trading as Dragon advisory) and later another under a separate name called Naga Advisory. Dragon and Naga have advised clients such as the [[Kingdom of Bahrain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bahrainwatch.org/pr/dragon-associates.php|title=Dragon Associates &#124; PR Watch|website=bahrainwatch.org}}</ref> Other clients included [[5 Hertford Street]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://events.5hertfordstreet.com/home/|title=5 Hertford Street Events|website=5 Hertford Street Private Members Club Homepage}}</ref>, [[Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Marex Spectron]], and at Naga Advisory the Government Communications Office of Qatar. He also founded Drake Financial Advisory Limited with his wife Helene Schutrumpf in 2016. It was through working on the public relations for The Carnegie Club at Skibo Castle that he met [[Ellis Short]], owner of Skibo Castle and at that time also the owner of Sunderland AFC, that enabled him to negotiate its sale to Madrox PLC and become a shareholder himself as a reward from the other shareholders he brought in for arranging the deal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-7100729/Sunderland-owner-Stewart-Donald-sell-shares-investor-Mark-Campbell-set-charge.html/|title=Sunderland owner Stewart Donald in line to sell majority of his shares in League One club just 13 months after buying Black Cats with US investor Mark Campbell set to take charge|first=Matt|last=Lawton|date=3 June 2019|work=The Daily Mail}}</ref>. In 2017, [[Spear's Wealth Management Survey]] rated him among the top-10 public relations consultants in London in their annual rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spearswms.com/charlie-methven/|title=CHARLIE METHVEN|website=spearswms.com}}</ref>\n\n==Football clubs==\n\n===Oxford United F.C.===\n\nA life-long supporter of Oxford United F.C., Methven became a founding committee member of Oxford's supporters' trust, OxVox. In 2011, he became a Trustee of OUFC's Youth and Community Trust, founded supporters group the Yellow Army<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oufc.co.uk/news/2013/july/yellow-army/|title=Yellow Army|website=oufc.co.uk}}</ref> and also gave marketing and PR advice to the club's then owner Ian Lenagan, until Lenagan sold Oxford in 2014. Methven had launched an attempt to buy the club with subsequent business partner Stewart Donald, but was outbid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/sport/11318106.consortium-led-charlie-methven-launches-formal-bid-oxford-united/|title=Consortium led by Charlie Methven launches formal bid for Oxford United|website=Oxford Mail}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.a-love-supreme.com/post/2018/05/26/pizzas-pints-with-charlie-methven|title=Post|website=alovesupreme}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland A.F.C.===\n\nIn May 2018, Methven arranged for [[Juan Sartori]] and [[Stewart Donald]] to buy Sunderland AFC from American billionaire [[Ellis Short]]. Methven bought 6% of the club and was appointed as its Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/all-about/charlie-methven|title=Charlie Methven \u2013 Latest news, transfers, pictures, video, opinion \u2013 Chronicle Live|website=chroniclelive.co.uk}}</ref> The takeover is featured in Episode 8 of Netflix documentary [[Sunderland 'Til I Die]]: A Fresh Start. Prior to SAFC's acquisition by Donald, Sartori, and Methven it had been relegated twice consecutively and was \u00a3160&nbsp;million in debt and losing over \u00a320&nbsp;million per annum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/29/sunderland-overcame-trauma-double-relegation-reconnect-fans/|title=How Sunderland overcame trauma of a double relegation to reconnect with fans and rise from the dead|first=Luke|last=Edwards|date=29 March 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> The club had been expected by many industry experts to be on the brink of administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/apr/23/sunderland-what-next-debts-absent-owner|title=Large debts, absent owner, no identity \u2013 what next for Sunderland? &#124; Louise Taylor|first=Louise|last=Taylor|date=23 April 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.true-faith.co.uk/sunderland-finances-no-future/|title=SUNDERLAND FINANCES \u2013 NO FUTURE!|first=Michael|last=Martin|date=28 December 2017}}</ref> Undertaking a harsh restructuring, the group managed to turn around Sunderland's business fortunes fairly swiftly.\n\nMethven's time as Executive Director of Sunderland was marked by highs and lows. Under his marketing guidance, the club achieved the highest-ever season average attendance for the 3rd tier of English football (31,500),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderland-smash-league-one-average-16186108|title=Sunderland to smash League One average attendance over a season record on Saturday|first=Craig|last=Johns|date=26 April 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref> the highest single-match attendance for League 1 (46,039 vs Bradford City on Boxing Day 2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46614780|title=Sunderland 1-0 Bradford City: 46,039 crowd 'rewarded' by League One victory|date=26 December 2018|via=bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/sunderland-smash-attendance-record-almost-13779388|title=Sunderland smash attendance record as almost 50,000 fans attend Boxing Day clash|first=Simon|last=Bird|date=26 December 2018|website=mirror}}</ref> and the highest revenues in League 1 history. SAFC also received Football Business\u2019 Marketing Award for season 2018/2019 for the club's \u2018Big Seat Change\u2019 initiative and was nominated by the Football Supporters Association for their Best Fan Engagement award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sunderlands-pink-seat-replacement-scheme-14855809|title=Sunderland's 'pink seat' replacement scheme will make fans feel part of the club \u2013 just like I did|first=Rob|last=Mason|date=3 July 2018|website=nechronicle}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.safc.com:443/news/club-news/2018/september/football-business-awards-nomination|title=Big Seat Change recognised|date=27 September 2018|website=Sunderland Association Football Club}}</ref>\nHowever, he also ran into trouble with fan groups on two occasions. In a BBC Radio Newcastle interview in September 2018, he described Sunderland fans who chose to watch illegal live streams in pubs adjoining the stadium instead of paying to watch matches as \u2018parasites\u2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/16904424.sunderland-director-charlie-methven-hits-parasites/|title=Sunderland director Charlie Methven hits out at \"parasites\"|website=The Northern Echo}}</ref> a word he subsequently described as \"ill-chosen\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokerreport.sbnation.com/2018/11/28/18115979/news-sunderland-executive-director-charlie-methven-clarifies-ill-chosen-parasites-comment|title=News: Sunderland Executive Director Charlie Methven clarifies \"ill-chosen\" parasites comment|first=Andy|last=Tomlinson|date=28 November 2018|website=Roker Report}}</ref> Over a year later, he was the subject of a leak from a private meeting with fans group leaders. Methven had asked during the meeting if the reason why supporters were critical of a \u00a310&nbsp;million investment he had arranged in the club was that fewer of them had worked in entrepreneurial businesses than would be the case in the south of the UK, and were therefore suspicious of private sector investment. He explained to The Times, who published the leak, that he had \"felt exasperated\" by the negative reaction to something he regarded as good news and had reacted \"intemperately\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunderland-director-enraged-northern-fans-by-claiming-they-do-not-understand-business-mjqz9gh7d|title=Sunderland director enraged northern fans by claiming they do not understand business|first=Matt Lawton, Chief Sports Correspondent &#124; Martin Hardy, Northern Sports|last=Correspondent|work=The Times}}</ref>\n\nBy this time, Methven had already announced his resignation from Sunderland's Board, eventually stepping down in December 2019 citing the pressures of business and family life. He explained in a statement that his wife was in the latter stages of pregnancy and that his consultancy clients expected him to be in London more often in 2020. He continued as a shareholder of the club, and as a director of its holding company, Madrox PLC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/charlie-methven-sunderland-steps-down-17374484|title=Sunderland director Charlie Methven announces his resignation from the board|first=James|last=Hunter|date=6 December 2019|website=nechronicle}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Methven, Charlie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Sayakayaraya", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePublic relations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Methven"}
